      <div class="faq-section">
        <h2>Frequently Asked Questions (FAQ)</h2>

        <details class="faq-item">
          <summary><h3>What is the main difference between options and stocks?</h3></summary>
          <p>The main difference is ownership. When you buy a stock, you own a literal piece of the company, entitling you to voting rights and potential dividends. When you buy an option, you simply own a temporary derivative contract that gives you the right to buy or sell that stock at a specific price by a certain expiration date.</p>
        </details>

        <details class="faq-item">
          <summary><h3>Are options riskier than stocks?</h3></summary>
          <p>Yes, generally options are substantially riskier because they involve extreme leverage and have a hard expiration date. If the stock doesn't move in the exact direction you predicted before that expiration date, an option can expire completely worthless, resulting in a 100% loss of your invested capital. Stocks, however, rarely go to zero quickly and can be held indefinitely to recover losses.</p>
        </details>

        <details class="faq-item">
          <summary><h3>Can you lose more than you invest in options?</h3></summary>
          <p>It depends heavily on the specific type of trade. If you only <em>buy</em> options (long calls or long puts), the absolute maximum you can lose is the initial premium you paid for the contract. However, if you <em>sell</em> (write) naked options, your potential losses can be mathematically unlimited if the stock moves violently against you.</p>
        </details>

        <details class="faq-item">
          <summary><h3>Do options pay dividends?</h3></summary>
          <p>No, options absolutely do not pay dividends. Only the underlying stockholders of record receive corporate dividend payments. If you want to receive a dividend while holding a call option, you must formally exercise your call option to buy the underlying stock before the official ex-dividend date to capture the payout.</p>
        </details>

        <details class="faq-item">
          <summary><h3>Why do people trade options instead of just buying stocks?</h3></summary>
          <p>Investors trade options primarily for immense leverage (controlling 100 shares for a fraction of the cost, leading to much higher percentage returns on capital), for hedging against potential market crashes in their existing stock portfolio, or for generating consistent monthly income by strategically selling options contracts to other speculators.</p>
        </details>
